---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = 'Playwright MCP in Cursor: IDE-Native Test Creation';
const date = 'March 26, 2026';
const readTime = '7 min read';

const snippetMcpConfig = `// Cursor → Settings → MCP (or .cursor/mcp.json)
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "playwright": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["@playwright/mcp@latest"]
    }
  }
}`;

const snippetTestSketch = `import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('happy path checkout with test data', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/checkout');
  await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Pay now' }).click();
  await expect(page.getByText('Payment successful')).toBeVisible();
});`;
---

<BaseLayout
  locale="en"
  title={`${title} — Santiago Zapata Mejía`}
  description="Connect Playwright’s official MCP server in Cursor to inspect the real app and design E2E tests faster."
>
  <article class="article">
    <div class="article-container">
      <a href="/en/blog" class="back-link">
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none"><path d="M13 8H3M7 4L3 8l4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path></svg>
        Back to blog
      </a>

      <header class="article-header fade-in">
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span class="article-tag">Playwright + Cursor</span>
          <span class="article-date">{date} · {readTime}</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="article-title">{title}</h1>
        <p class="article-subtitle">
          The Model Context Protocol lets tools like Cursor drive a real browser through Playwright. You stop guessing selectors in a vacuum and start authoring
          tests against live DOM and network behavior.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="article-body fade-in">
        <h2>Why this beats “chat-only” workflows</h2>
        <p>
          A plain LLM can hallucinate locators or flows that never existed. With the <strong>Playwright MCP server</strong>, the assistant can (depending on tool
          configuration) open URLs, take accessibility-oriented snapshots, interact with the page, and return real UI structure. Your job is to turn that into
          <code>getByRole</code>, <code>getByTestId</code>, or POM methods that compile and pass in CI.
        </p>

        <h2>Wiring Playwright MCP into Cursor</h2>
        <p>
          Microsoft publishes a Playwright MCP package (<span class="tok">@playwright/mcp</span>). Add it as an MCP server in Cursor settings or your project
          config. Minimal example:
        </p>
        <pre class="mono-block"><span class="mono-inner">{snippetMcpConfig}</span></pre>
        <p>
          After saving, restart or reload MCP in Cursor. Approve network access the first time (<span class="tok">npx</span> pulls what it needs). In corporate
          environments, pin the package version in <span class="tok">args</span> instead of <span class="tok">@latest</span> for reproducible builds.
        </p>

        <h2>A workflow that exploits test creation</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Run the app</strong> locally or point at staging; keep <span class="tok">baseURL</span> in <span class="tok">playwright.config</span> as usual.</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Ask for a snapshot</strong> after navigating to the flow you want (login, checkout, settings). Snapshots expose refs and visible text — far
            more reliable than dumping raw HTML into chat.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Iterate in the IDE:</strong> have the agent draft a <code>test.describe</code> with <code>test.step</code> labels, <code>expect</code>
            assertions, and locators that prefer roles and accessible names.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Paste into your repo</strong>, run <span class="tok">npx playwright test</span>, tighten test data, and add negative cases the MCP will not
            replace (business rules, permissions, empty states).
          </li>
        </ol>

        <h2>From draft to a maintainable suite</h2>
        <p>
          MCP accelerates <em>discovery</em>; suite quality is still yours. Encapsulate with Page Objects, prefer API-based auth fixtures when possible, and avoid
          volatile CSS classes. A typical skeleton after an agent session:
        </p>
        <pre class="mono-block"><span class="mono-inner">{snippetTestSketch}</span></pre>

        <h2>Limitations worth internalizing</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>It does not replace data policies, API contracts, or human review of business assertions.</li>
          <li>Behind heavy auth, seed cookies/tokens or a stable login path before asking for long automation.</li>
          <li>Iframes and locked-down environments may limit what the server exposes — document those paths and test them separately.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Bottom line: <strong>MCP + Cursor + Playwright</strong> is a huge lever from idea to runnable tests; treat agent output as a professional draft, not
          ground truth. For full-suite patterns, see
          <a href="https://github.com/ZapataMejia/playwright-automation-framework" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">playwright-automation-framework</a>
          for POM + CI structure I still use as a reference.
        </p>

        <div class="article-author">
          <div class="author-info">
            <div class="author-avatar">SZ</div>
            <div>
              <div class="author-name">Santiago Zapata Mejía</div>
              <div class="author-role">QA Automation Lead · Speaker at QAConf Eje Cafetero</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <a href="/en/blog" class="back-link back-link-bottom">
        <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none"><path d="M13 8H3M7 4L3 8l4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path></svg>
        Back to blog
      </a>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
